{"key":"processedPost-16782236","value":{"id":16782236,"first":16780682,"last":18056000,"when":1346708449,"utime":"09/04/12 12:40 AM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><b>JostVanDyke said:</b><br /><br />As endospore germination was the main focus of the soak in earlier years, it has become less and less of a talking point and grains softening has been the main issue as of late.<br /><br />Soaking for 4 hours allows the grain to soften up enough for them to be boiled without many grains exploding releasing ooze that bacteria and other contamination love to grow on.<br /></blockquote><br /><br />Soaking for at least four hours hydrates not just the grains so they soften, but it also hydrates the endospores, whether or not they have time to germinate.&nbsp; If the bacterial endospores are in their hard shell covering, they can survive.&nbsp; If it's softened, they get nuked.<br /><br />One should avoid pouring boiling water over dry grains as this can lead to burst kernels.<br />RR","title":"Re: 2012 Grain soaking discussion.","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}